And in this moment,

19:02.850 --> 19:08.497
He delays what you see now that the verse 10 says, if we had not delayed, we would have been able to return twice.

19:08.558 --> 19:10.660
He's delayed and he's frozen.

19:12.383 --> 19:16.488
In the midst of like this big opportunity to provide and care for his family, he freezes.

19:17.349 --> 19:20.593
And I know what it's like to be a guy, because I am one.

19:22.035 --> 19:27.502
But I know, man, one of the things you think about when you're laying in your bed at night is you think about this.

19:28.103 --> 19:30.226
You think about life and intruder breaks into the house.

19:31.010 --> 19:39.438
I'm gonna stand in the bowl, I'm gonna make sure my family, I know how my family's gonna get out of here, they're gonna jump out that window right there, and I'm gonna delay as long as I can, even if it costs my life.

19:39.458 --> 19:41.180
If you think about those moments, I know you do.

19:42.301 --> 19:44.103
Not all the time, but you do think you have those thoughts.

19:44.964 --> 19:54.573
And here he had that moment where he could actually lay down his life and say, hey, I'm gonna sacrifice myself, make sure we get the grain, so feed my family, and he freezes.

19:54.613 --> 19:57.276
He fails in that moment.

19:57.296 --> 19:59.218
And I think this happens often to men

20:00.130 --> 20:09.801
when uncontrollable situations happen in life and you don't know what to do, we either freeze and we panic or we blow up and we explode on people.

20:10.341 --> 20:25.258
Think about this, if you're overwhelmed at work and you come home and you start getting bombarded with questions and even simple, innocent questions and you either withdraw and you just kind of stare blankly at them and it's like, hey, where are you?

20:25.678 --> 20:29.202
Or you snap and ignore and then you

20:29.602 --> 20:33.066
Well, I can't deal with all this nonsense at home.

20:33.126 --> 20:36.410
And so I'm just going to pour myself into what I'm good at.

20:36.991 --> 20:38.212
And this is what men struggle with.

20:38.232 --> 20:39.854
They pour themselves into their competencies.

20:40.055 --> 20:42.397
We're not good in the areas that we're struggling.

20:42.417 --> 20:45.782
And so I'm just going to feel good about myself and pour myself into my competencies.

20:45.802 --> 20:49.766
And this is honestly what a lot of what leads to workaholism is this.

20:50.387 --> 20:51.889
I feel like I can do my work well.

20:52.289 --> 20:52.990
I know how to do that.

20:53.090 --> 20:56.114
I don't know how to deal with this problem over here.

20:56.642 --> 21:00.767
It's probably better for everybody if I just go ahead and just stay at work or money.

21:01.488 --> 21:04.051
This is a problem for us.

21:04.071 --> 21:13.362
And in this moment of Jacob freezing this failure of leadership where the family needs someone to lead them, here steps Judah.

21:14.524 --> 21:16.586
I remember Judah's story for just a second.

21:16.666 --> 21:22.193
This is a man who, it was his idea to actually sell Joseph to the caravan that was passing by.

21:22.213 --> 21:26.578
Oh yeah, Judah also, I think this is Genesis 37.

21:26.946 --> 21:28.449
or they're about, what did he do?

21:28.489 --> 21:33.339
He sleeps with his daughter-in-law and his excuse for it was, he thought she was a prostitute.

21:33.459 --> 21:34.902
So he's like, ah, it's probably fine.

21:36.185 --> 21:36.666
It's wild.

21:37.668 --> 21:43.660
You know, not who you would expect to be the hero of the story, but God has been forming him and drawing him to himself.

21:44.261 --> 21:46.886
And this is what he says in verse eight to nine.

21:46.926 --> 21:48.850
And Judah said that Israel, his father,

21:50.562 --> 21:56.929
Send the boy with me, and we will arise and go that we may live and not die, both we and you and also our little ones.

21:57.390 --> 21:58.831
I will be a pledge for his safety.

21:58.871 --> 22:00.533
From my hand, you shall require him.

22:02.516 --> 22:09.023
If I do not bring him back to you and set him before you, then let me bear the blame forever."

22:10.685 --> 22:14.209
It's a pretty powerful statement for that guy to be able to say.

22:15.510 --> 22:18.674
God has been slowly turning him into a godly man.

22:19.074 --> 22:21.898
He's offering to die for his brother, and this is wild on a couple fronts.

22:21.918 --> 22:24.221
For one, if you remember Jacob, I had two wives.

22:24.241 --> 22:26.704
He had his wife, Lea, and his wife Rachel.

22:26.784 --> 22:27.926
Rachel, he loved Lea.

22:27.946 --> 22:28.467
He did not.

22:29.909 --> 22:34.114
Rachel had two sons, Joseph, who they sold in the slave of the first time.

22:34.154 --> 22:38.580
And it's one of the reasons why Joseph got sold in the slave of his because he was a favorite, because he was the oldest from the favorite wife.

22:39.582 --> 22:42.706
And her other son was the youngest son, which is Benjamin.

22:43.266 --> 22:47.812
And he got Jude over here, and there's been this tension between the layer and the line of Rachel.

22:47.832 --> 22:48.653
They don't like each other.

22:48.793 --> 22:49.935
They're playing favorites.

22:49.955 --> 22:50.796
And now you get Judah.

22:51.857 --> 22:54.641
He's the oldest brother now in the house with seeming in prison in Egypt.

22:55.202 --> 23:00.288
And Judah says, listen, I will die even for my rival, my rival brother.

23:00.749 --> 23:02.912
I will pledge my life for him.

23:03.032 --> 23:04.294
This is not a small change.

23:04.494 --> 23:05.255
This is massive.

23:05.876 --> 23:10.642
He who once was willing to sell his brother in, now he's willing to put his life as a pledge for him.

23:11.266 --> 23:16.531
He also doesn't like minimize the danger here and pretend like, hey, this is not that big of a deal.

23:16.551 --> 23:17.492
I'm sure it'll be fine.

23:17.532 --> 23:19.594
He knows it might not be fine.

23:20.055 --> 23:21.837
And he doesn't have like a big plan either.

23:22.958 --> 23:28.924
He shows us the beginning of leadership is being able to walk into the dark even when you don't know the outcome.

23:29.725 --> 23:31.446
And this is the first thing we learn about leadership.

23:31.486 --> 23:34.990
There's two aspects to what it means to what our leadership looks like.

23:35.010 --> 23:38.994
The first thing we learn about leadership is to lead us to take responsibility.

23:40.962 --> 23:42.624
To lead is to take responsibility.

23:42.664 --> 23:49.932
Leadership is not about competence, it's not about certainty, but about taking responsibility.

23:50.713 --> 23:58.942
Even if you think about the Bible, remember Moses, Moses who goes and rescues the people from the promise, and he has to have someone else speak for him, right?

23:59.923 --> 24:00.804
It's kind of interesting.

24:01.685 --> 24:10.194
It's not about his competence, it's not about his certainty, it's about him taking responsibility and leading, and this is what he does, he pledges his life for his brother.

24:12.002 --> 24:13.043
His family needs food.

24:13.564 --> 24:14.705
He will do what he needs to do.

24:14.765 --> 24:17.989
He will take responsibility to go get it.

24:19.632 --> 24:27.121
Another word for responsibility here, and this idea that I've hinted at in the introduction is the idea of covenant headship.

24:28.743 --> 24:32.668
This idea of covenant headship, this is how God deals with his people through representatives.

24:33.449 --> 24:37.714
And the way he does is that representative takes responsibility for the actions of the people.

24:38.818 --> 24:44.364
It's not because they're smarter, it's not because they're more gifted necessarily, but it's called, they're called to carry the burden.

24:45.906 --> 24:59.881
And then the first way you were called to lead in this world, in your family, in your life, is by taking responsibility, by being slow to blame, by not following Adam, which we're always a little bit quick to blame.

25:00.682 --> 25:07.890
And then when we are quick to blame, and we realize, we're like, no, it's Adam's fault, which is kind of funny, because then you're blaming Adam for it.

25:08.546 --> 25:09.467
It's a good joke, Craig.

25:12.993 --> 25:19.382
But this is the kind of men that we need to be, be slow to blame, quick to be able to carry the burden, quick to take responsibility.

25:19.402 --> 25:24.229
When things go sideways, even when it's not our fault, we'll quick to stand in and take responsibility.

25:25.111 --> 25:29.317
Which leads to the second aspect of leadership, which is sacrifice, right?

25:29.477 --> 25:35.346
And this is where Judas pledge here, willing to sacrifice himself for his brother,

25:37.666 --> 25:38.487
What else does he say?

25:38.547 --> 25:43.856
If I do not bring him back to you and set him before you, then let me bear the blame forever.

25:43.916 --> 25:58.418
This kind of sacrifice that he's willing to take, even setting the blame for the rest of his life if something bad happens, is a foreshadow of his future offspring who is Jesus himself.

25:59.490 --> 26:07.618
Jesus, the true covenant head, the one who never fails in leadership, the one who never fails to bear responsibility for his people on himself.

26:07.658 --> 26:09.419
And what does that bearing responsibility look like?

26:09.459 --> 26:11.121
It looks like sacrifice.

26:12.322 --> 26:20.049
I mean, Jesus himself said, he said, in Mark 10, the Son of Man came not to be served, but to serve and to offer his life as a ransom for many.

26:20.069 --> 26:25.374
This is why Jesus came, to serve, to lay his life down.

26:25.455 --> 26:27.356
And this is what leadership looks like.

26:27.416 --> 26:29.138
It looks like dying to self.

26:31.554 --> 26:33.878
This is also a theme that's picked up in Ephesians 5.

26:34.139 --> 26:38.867
You know, at the beginning of that section, it says, wives, submit to your husbands.

26:39.448 --> 26:42.373
I was unto the Lord, and then it says, husbands, love your wives.

26:42.513 --> 26:43.655
Does Christ love the church?

26:43.896 --> 26:44.757
How do Christ love the church?

26:44.837 --> 26:46.540
Laying his life down for her.

26:47.241 --> 26:48.083
This is how you lead.

26:48.103 --> 26:49.746
You lead by death, by dying.

26:50.487 --> 26:54.514
And there's sometimes people can view this kind of act of service, servant leadership.

26:54.722 --> 26:56.846
There's almost like a weakness to it.

26:57.146 --> 27:00.913
Some people mock this idea of servant leadership, like it's a cowardice, like you're just leading from behind.

27:00.933 --> 27:02.515
I mean, you don't want to take charge out in front.

27:02.896 --> 27:06.041
So you're just kind of, I'm just going to lead in the back and be passive and be sheepish.

27:06.582 --> 27:08.485
That is not what the picture is here.

27:09.687 --> 27:13.294
Servant leadership, what it does is it recognizes the point of leading.

27:13.955 --> 27:20.626
The point of leading anybody, any group of people is actually to serve them, to serve their needs.

27:21.250 --> 27:35.086
It's a kind of leadership that says, I'm gonna act in the best interest of this group of people, even when it is against my best interest, which obviously there's no great example in Christ for him to work on behalf of the interests of his people, amid his own death.

27:36.968 --> 27:39.892
It's a courageous movement towards danger for the sake of others.

27:42.154 --> 27:43.055
That's what we're called to.

27:46.159 --> 27:48.722
This is what God has called you to in this room.

27:50.498 --> 27:53.583
If you think about if you're a boy in this room, you're a little boy.

27:53.603 --> 27:56.248
If you're a little boy, look at me for a second.

27:56.268 --> 27:57.870
You know, God gave you something right here.

27:57.910 --> 27:58.752
What do He give you right here?

27:58.772 --> 28:00.655
He gave you muscles, right?

28:01.376 --> 28:02.117
He made you strong.

28:03.399 --> 28:05.543
Little boys, why did God make you strong?

28:07.246 --> 28:09.269
Is it to beat up on your sister and brothers?

28:10.151 --> 28:10.451
Well, no.

28:11.353 --> 28:13.035
But that's not what God gave you muscles for.

28:13.436 --> 28:17.042
Scripture tells us that the glory of a man is his strength.

28:18.338 --> 28:23.283
You know when that glory of your muscles is seen most clearly and your strength is seen most clearly?

28:27.308 --> 28:29.951
Is when you use it to serve the needs of others.

28:31.793 --> 28:42.784
That glory is seen most clearly when you give away your strength to serve, not to dominate others, not to lead in fear, but to lead by bearing the responsibility and sacrifice.

28:42.804 --> 28:44.306
That is what God has made you strong.

28:45.794 --> 28:49.460
So the first thing we discover about the call of men here in this text is men are called to lead.

28:50.621 --> 28:54.608
And that leadership looks like taking responsibility.

28:55.489 --> 29:00.457
It looks like sacrificing, seeing the need of others before yourself.

29:00.477 --> 29:05.705
It's the first question you need to ask yourself for the men in this room is where do you struggle to take responsibility?

29:07.047 --> 29:08.950
Where are those little times in life where you're quick to blame?

29:10.572 --> 29:13.116
What do you struggle to put others' needs before your own?

29:13.136 --> 29:14.258
Where do you selfish?

29:15.266 --> 29:20.274
using your strength, your talents to make yourself comfortable.

29:21.556 --> 29:33.374
The first area of encouragement we need in this calling of manhood is this encouragement to lead, which leads to this other side of the coin of manhood, which is love.

29:33.435 --> 29:34.556
So first, we're called to lead.

29:34.636 --> 29:36.880
Second, we are, men are called to love.

29:38.563 --> 29:43.250
This is an essential piece and often neglected.

29:43.746 --> 29:48.411
We're not just called to be cold men who stoically lead and are super serious all the time.

29:48.972 --> 29:49.833
It's not what we're called to.

29:50.393 --> 29:51.114
We're called to love.

29:51.134 --> 29:54.998
We're called to a tenderheartedness towards the people around us.

29:55.579 --> 29:58.322
And this is actually what you see in the character of Joseph.

30:00.724 --> 30:01.905
We see that they finally go back.

30:01.946 --> 30:06.530
This is their second journey into Egypt to get more food and they're invited into the house.

30:06.931 --> 30:11.436
And remember, this has been 22 years since Joseph has encountered his brothers.

30:11.696 --> 30:13.618
So his brothers do not know who he is.

30:15.266 --> 30:19.411
And if you think about Joseph's life in these last 22 years, it haven't been great.

30:19.431 --> 30:31.425
He's been in prison, which doesn't sound like a great time, but God has been preparing him in this prison, and Joseph has become a very capable man.

30:31.865 --> 30:42.578
He's second in command in the greatest nation at the time in Egypt, and he is saving the entire ancient Near East from famine and death.

30:45.570 --> 30:57.730
No one would blame Joseph if he became a little bit colder, if he became a bit detached, emotionally detached, if he was a little bit hardened and even vindictive based on everything that happened to him.

30:58.051 --> 31:00.455
No one would blame him for this.

31:00.475 --> 31:09.269
But God has been forming him quietly in the dark and has turned him into a different kind of person, a person that's amazing to see.

31:10.391 --> 31:12.114
We see as he's coming

31:13.794 --> 31:23.625
As he comes before his brothers, says this in verse 27, and he inquired about their welfare and said, is your father well, the old man of whom he spoke?

31:23.685 --> 31:24.305
Is he alive?

31:24.325 --> 31:27.489
I mean, his first instinct is, is my dad alive?

31:27.509 --> 31:28.890
Am I going to get to see my dad again?

31:29.411 --> 31:30.011
He's not angry.

31:31.533 --> 31:32.594
Not angry at his brothers either.

31:32.614 --> 31:34.536
He's like, am I going to see my father?

31:35.958 --> 31:38.441
And then he says, is my brother there?

31:38.721 --> 31:39.722
Is this my brother?

31:39.822 --> 31:40.503
Is this my young brother?

31:40.523 --> 31:42.685
Obviously, he's not going to recognize him 22 years later.

31:42.705 --> 31:43.506
He wouldn't know.

31:43.778 --> 31:46.942
from just seeing him to say, yeah, this is Benjamin.

31:48.183 --> 31:54.892
And this whole moment of coming before his brothers overwhelms him in verse 30.

31:55.332 --> 32:02.221
And Joseph hurried out for his compassion grew warm for his brother and he sat a place to weep and he entered his chamber and wept there.

32:03.462 --> 32:09.970
The scene over at Womson, this isn't weakness, this is not just sentimentality, this is a tender heart.

32:10.946 --> 32:15.010
This is a profound love and he's not hiding his tears because of embarrassment.

32:15.491 --> 32:20.436
I mean, two chapters later in chapter 45, he openly weeps in front and with his brothers.

32:21.397 --> 32:24.401
So this isn't the time that he wasn't ready to reveal himself to them yet.

32:24.441 --> 32:25.462
That's what's happening here.

32:25.482 --> 32:30.187
He still has one more test to get to his brothers to see if they've changed, if they've grown.

32:30.247 --> 32:32.609
This isn't weakness.

32:33.010 --> 32:34.131
This is a tender hardiness.

32:34.291 --> 32:36.914
This is a man who has grown into a godly man.

32:38.434 --> 32:40.897
And as you grow into godliness, you grow in compassion.

32:42.600 --> 32:44.162
A godly man is not domineering.

32:44.202 --> 32:46.365
He's not cold-hearted.

32:47.607 --> 32:55.898
He's not quick to violence or anger, which violence and anger miss where you can misuse strength easily in those two subjects.

32:57.180 --> 32:58.642
A godly man is a man of love.

33:00.725 --> 33:04.490
A man of tender-heartedness, especially towards his family.

33:05.712 --> 33:07.314
This is where many men struggle.

33:09.570 --> 33:11.853
Many men struggle with this tender hardiness.

33:12.113 --> 33:14.997
There's probably two different kinds of men in this room.

33:15.017 --> 33:17.140
There's gonna be some men that don't struggle with this part.

33:17.160 --> 33:22.908
You struggle with the latter, whereas some of you are gonna struggle with leadership and taking responsibility.

33:22.948 --> 33:27.995
And you're gonna be a tenderhearted person that say, I'm really tenderhearted.

33:28.015 --> 33:30.799
You can come to me, you can tell me anything, but I'm not gonna take responsibility.

33:31.620 --> 33:33.583
I'm not gonna work hard in those ways.

33:34.084 --> 33:35.105
Others are the opposite.

33:35.125 --> 33:38.770
And this is where probably most fall, especially in a farming area,

33:39.074 --> 33:41.837
I grew up with farmers, by farmers.

33:42.077 --> 33:42.738
I know what it's like.

33:43.399 --> 33:45.701
They're not the most tender-hearted, loving people.

33:47.022 --> 33:49.165
You grow up and you learn, hey, I'm going to take responsibility.

33:50.086 --> 33:50.847
I'm going to serve.

33:50.867 --> 33:51.707
I'm going to sacrifice.

33:51.768 --> 33:52.508
I'll do that all day.

33:52.528 --> 33:53.710
I'll take a bowl for my family.

33:54.751 --> 33:55.712
But I'm not tender-hearted.

33:56.192 --> 33:57.193
I'm not very emotional.

33:57.694 --> 33:59.256
I never tell people I love them.

34:00.717 --> 34:05.362
Usually we fall on either side of the coin, where our natural tendencies are one or the other.

34:06.370 --> 34:13.783
But the biblical vision of what a godly man looks like is both called the lead out of strength and out of love.

34:15.185 --> 34:19.773
And one of these without the other is always corrupt, right?

34:20.794 --> 34:26.304
If you have authority without compassion, I mean, that's what toxic masculinity is.

34:27.386 --> 34:29.890
Is that authority piece without any kind of compassion.

34:31.192 --> 34:32.434
But if you have compassion,

34:32.738 --> 34:38.025
Without any kind of responsibility, that's this unstable masculinity, and that's not gonna go anywhere either.

34:39.067 --> 34:40.389
The church needs both from you.

34:40.989 --> 34:45.736
The world needs both, your wife needs both, that your children need both from you.

34:47.919 --> 34:58.834
Now, although this is a beautiful vision, beautiful vision of the completeness of manhood that has a strength to lead and bear responsibility and sacrifice, but it has a compassion to weep and cry with you,

34:59.586 --> 35:00.167
Yes, amen.

35:00.207 --> 35:01.589
It's a beautiful vision.

35:01.629 --> 35:03.331
And if you're a man here, you're like, that's what I want.

35:03.351 --> 35:04.713
But this is the challenge too.

35:05.534 --> 35:09.939
This is where you're going to feel the weight of your failures just come, you know, where you're strong and weak.

35:10.019 --> 35:10.801
I know where I'm strong.

35:10.861 --> 35:16.408
My kids, probably my wife, everyone who lives with you knows where you're strong in this and where you're weak in this.

35:17.449 --> 35:19.312
And this is the, this is the great challenge.

35:19.332 --> 35:21.314
How do we not just bear shame in our inability?

35:21.354 --> 35:24.799
I mean, and we've so rarely seen this combination.

35:24.859 --> 35:27.442
Is this even possible?

35:28.354 --> 35:31.821
Is this an impossible endeavor to try to grow in both of these ways?

35:31.941 --> 35:35.348
Is this just an idealism that we're just going to be like, well, I'm never going to be like that.

35:35.388 --> 35:37.432
Moving on, might as well not even try.

35:37.492 --> 35:45.608
The only way it's not impossible is when you look to Christ, because this perfectly describes the man that Christ was.

35:45.648 --> 35:47.471
He's the lion and the what?

35:48.333 --> 35:48.914
And the lamb.

35:49.634 --> 36:00.646
He's the one who, out of fierce anger, turned over tables who stepped in front of the stones and protected a prostitute who says as a sword coming out of his mouth and robes dipped in blood.

36:00.666 --> 36:01.367
He's a warrior.

36:03.049 --> 36:04.510
He's the one who takes responsibility.

36:04.550 --> 36:07.033
He's the one who leads and sacrifices for his people.

36:07.073 --> 36:07.734
He's strong.

36:09.616 --> 36:10.997
But Jesus also tells us he's what?

36:11.017 --> 36:13.100
He's gentle and lowly.

36:15.522 --> 36:18.866
Jesus is the one who weeps when his friend dies.

36:20.194 --> 36:21.175
He's tenderhearted.

36:22.036 --> 36:23.978
He is the lamb led, the slaughter.

36:26.421 --> 36:27.622
This is who Christ is.

36:27.662 --> 36:29.004
He is our model.

36:29.044 --> 36:34.650
He is the one true man, the true Adam that we are growing and maturing into.

36:34.690 --> 36:39.215
It is not possible to get there naturally though.

36:40.156 --> 36:40.556
You know, C.S.

36:40.616 --> 36:43.019
Lewis has this essay on medieval chivalry.

36:43.900 --> 36:49.746
And in this essay, he talks about this kind of vision of masculinity and the strength

36:50.178 --> 36:58.872
in the leadership, but also that having the humility and the softness as well, and that the nights of old had this unique combination.

36:59.994 --> 37:03.159
And he says this kind of man is not a product of nature.

37:04.300 --> 37:06.624
I mean, this kind of man is not just grown by accident.

37:08.527 --> 37:09.168
This is an art.

37:10.691 --> 37:13.255
And if an art, then it has an artist.

37:14.216 --> 37:17.842
And that artist is God himself working on us and through us.

37:18.850 --> 37:25.316
Growing into this kind of man is not possible on your own, but as we follow the one true man in Jesus, he will form you into this.

37:26.097 --> 37:32.944
And you know, there's this language about men having a quest, which is always a little bit cheesy, they call men, you need to have a quest.

37:33.004 --> 37:34.886
It's a little cheesy, but maybe it's a little bit true too.

37:35.206 --> 37:40.131
If you need a quest, this is the greatest quest you could have is to become this kind of man.

37:41.593 --> 37:44.115
